      <hedline>
        <hl1>Unfriendly Skies: What to Do?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Rep Jesse L Jackson Jr, prompted by Sept 5 article on crisis for air traffic system, says Federal Aviation Administration's call for new study rings hollow, given its knowledge of problems and inaction for so many years</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Crisis for Air Traffic System: More Passengers, More Delays'' (front page, Sept. 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Crisis for Air Traffic System: More Passengers, More Delays'' (front page, Sept. 5):</p>
        <p>Our aviation industry is a cornerstone of the global economy. Yet for years the Federal Aviation Administration ignored its own warnings about the system's reaching gridlock by 2000.</p>
        <p>The public and business world are now paying the price with record delays and cancellations, poor service, outdated technology and overburdened airports.</p>
        <p>One of the worst chokepoints is O'Hare International Airport. Sixteen years ago, the F.A.A. directed the State of Illinois to begin planning a third regional airport. Those plans are complete but have been stymied by the Clinton administration, bowing to pleas from Mayor Richard M. Daley and the airlines that control O'Hare.</p>
        <p>Now Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and the F.A.A. say that it's time to study aviation problems. But given the agency's knowledge of the problems and inaction, the call rings hollow.</p>
        <p>JESSE L. JACKSON JR.  Member of Congress, 2nd Dist., Ill.  Washington, Sept. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
